songs.title: A Perfect Miracle

description.plain:
On June 2, 2018, a long-running UK space-rock band Spiritualized removed all posts from their social media accounts to the band’s logo in front of a bright orange field except for a similarly bright orange video featuring a message in morse code. That message, both written out in dots and dashes and playing as a series of beeps, translates to the phrase “A Perfect Miracle.”
https://twitter.com/officialSpzd/status/1003006085064790016

“A Perfect Miracle” is also a song they’ve played live since 2012 but have yet to officially release.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BlaZIPwyOrE

description.plain:
While the literal interpretation of the song conjures up images of violence, the ‘gun’ being referred to in the lyrics may be an emotional weapon, rather than a physical one.

It seems that a father may have emotionally devastated his family at some point in the past by leaving them, and the subject of the song has followed in the same footsteps. The chorus exposes the regret of leaving, and a desire to return home.

songs.title: Home of the Brave

description.plain:
This song provides a contrasting verse-chorus form, in which the verses describe his current troubled state where he’s using substance abuse to cope with the absence of a loved one, versus the chorus which shows a willingness and determination for positive change.
The song starts off as soft as a lullaby with a very calming tone, which is gradually drowned-out by a loud and chaotic whirlwind of noise from various instruments, leading into the next song “The Individual”. Considering the lyrics, this gradual shift in atmosphere likely represents the effects of the drugs he had been using to numb the pain slowly fleeting away, as he’s ultimately confronted with his inner turmoil.

description.plain:
The groundbreaking “Ladies and Gentlemen We Are Floating in Space” comes from the album of the same name, released in June 1997. The song’s title comes from the novel Sophie’s World by Jostein Gaarder:

Only philosophers embark on this perilous expedition to the outermost reaches of language and existence. Some of them fall off, but others cling on desperately and yell at the people nestling deep in the snug softness, stuffing themselves with delicious food and drink. ‘Ladies and Gentlemen,’ they yell, ‘we are floating in space!’ But none of the people down there care.

Two versions of the song exist — the original, which incorporated Elvis’s “Can’t Help Falling In Love”, and an alternative that was used when the Presley estate refused permission for the use of the lyrics. The reissued album restores the original version.

The song is sung in the form of a round, where different lyrics are sung in succession but combine to create a harmony. Like countless songs, it borrows the timeless chord progression from Pachebel’s “Canon in D”.

body.plain:
The groundbreaking “Ladies and Gentlemen We Are Floating in Space” comes from the album of the same name, released in June 1997. The song’s title comes from the novel Sophie’s World by Jostein Gaarder:

Only philosophers embark on this perilous expedition to the outermost reaches of language and existence. Some of them fall off, but others cling on desperately and yell at the people nestling deep in the snug softness, stuffing themselves with delicious food and drink. ‘Ladies and Gentlemen,’ they yell, ‘we are floating in space!’ But none of the people down there care.

Two versions of the song exist — the original, which incorporated Elvis’s “Can’t Help Falling In Love”, and an alternative that was used when the Presley estate refused permission for the use of the lyrics. The reissued album restores the original version.

The song is sung in the form of a round, where different lyrics are sung in succession but combine to create a harmony. Like countless songs, it borrows the timeless chord progression from Pachebel’s “Canon in D”.

The song title is a play off of the famous The Crystals song “He Hit Me (And It Felt Like a Kiss)”, which came out in 1962.

The “she” in Pierce’s song is likely a reference to drugs, particularly heroin. Drugs are often personified as females. In this song, Pierce talks at length about self medicating to deal with his feelings and potential dope sickness (fever).
